Guarantee they have limited knowledge of AST's D2D satellite technology and how AST will benefit from the SDA program. To start, the SDA will order two satellites out of the gate. They said they would pay $14MM per satellite, which leaves AST a $10MM profit from each (assuming the military pays for launch, which it appears they do). The SDA also said they want to buy hundreds, yes, hundreds, of satellites in 2027. If you're a long-time investor of AST like I am, you know the previous positive catalysts and future ones to expect is why you're holding the stock. Smart play if you added to your position yesterday under $26. (I did). Will the stock be at $50 by December? Who knows? Safer guess is $100 or more in 2026 and higher each year after that. IMHO. Either way, I'm patient, which ain't easy because by human nature we're not. As WB said, "I didn't buy the stock; I bought the company."

Many of you here are as ignorant as a newborn newt in a desert.

I've been in the telecom industry for over 35 years.  For years it has been all but impossible to convert some clients from land lines to cellular or IP based communications due to the lack of available high speed uninterruptible and low latency signalling.  Cellular alone always a challenge for businesses that want to have communication control, but also because cellular costs and limitations often made it too expensive.  Using satellite in remote regions was great for Internet since the late CT was less of an issue for general use, but for OTT IP services such as voice was impractical.  I am sure everyone here has experienced latency on a call and it was if nothing else, a really lousy experience.  While Elon wants to use his fleet of Starlink for this is true, I don't think his small units are as robust as needed for the job if the whole planet or even just North America were to adopt.  including the fact that no companies can invest into the private Starlink company.  For ATT and Verizon, this apolitical company, a public company with transparency, it a perfect vehicle to become partners in this new exciting and much needed technology.

Comcast went with Starlink.  But, that is because Comcast themselves only have IP based phone services.  yes, they are an OTT on their own broadband, for many tax reasons and regulatory reasons.  Comcast cellular is just reselling a moderated Verizon service.  Perhaps they were going to negotiate using Starlink because it's ready and sounds cool, but at the end of the day that's small potatoes traffic.  Comcast just hoping to get a bang on marketing.

if any of you older folks are here, remember in the early 2000s when cell tower REITs were all the rage.  American Town, Crown Castle etc.  Those companies saw explosive growth over a ten year period especially when modern smart phones were introduced.  Now, running a REIT is t cheap.  leasing land or purchasing it and erecting steel towers or fake trees is expensive business with lots of costs associated.  Now, these same companies, American Tower certainly, are investing in this tower less company because they can see a partnership in the making, and a huge investment return on their part.  This is really the legit system that will be a game changer in global communications, starting with North America and expanding over time. 

Naysayers will be long forgotten in a couple years, trust me, long forgotten.  This company will mint many new millionaires and possible a billionaire or two.  The cost of deployment of this technology is far less than the overall cost of operating a full coverage REIT.  don't believe me?  then ask why some areas don't have coverage.  it's simple.  it's too expensive or impossible.  

Longs know this is a gem.  I can tell you very clearly that the margins on this will be insanely good.  and the services will be adopted because this technology is the only way to globalize communication once and for all.

I am all in on this company in terms of my beliefs and will be pouring in much of my portfolio as my other investments mature to the point that opportunity cost places me here which is rapidly coming.  Half a million $ in this company should make me a very handsome return in coming years, and I'll never ever worry about retirement.

From little bird, I don't know of any companies that have had both AT&T and Verizon as strategic partners and investors. However, when it comes to highly strategic assets, interestingly both AT&T and Verizon got into a massive bidding war in 2017 for a company called Straight Path that owned millimeter-wave spectrum (very very high band) in the 28 and 39 GHz bands. This spectrum was viewed as highly strategic for 5G deployment and both parties wanted to own it. Other than spectrum, Straight Path was basically a holding company and was losing gobs of money.
4/17/17: Initially AT&T announced a friendly deal for StraightPath for $95.63 per share or $1.6B EV, a 162% huge premium to the company's undisturbed share price of $36.48

4/25/17: Verizon submits unsolicited $104.64 per share proposal or $1.8B EV, a 187% premium to STRP undisturbed stock price. AT&T has a right to match this proposal. 

5/3/17: Verizon submits an increased offer of $135.96 per share or $2.3B EV, a 273% premium to the undisturbed stock price.

5/11/17: After back and forth negotiations with both AT&T and Verizon, Verizon enters into a definitive agreement to acquire Straight Path for $184 per share or $3.1B EV, a whopping 404% premium to the undisturbed share price.

Here is a rundown of policy differences. This is not an endorsement.Mr. Trump recently stated that he supports reducing the top corporate income tax bracketfrom 21% to 15% in order to help companies like ASTS to compete strongly against foreigncompetitors. 7 years ago, Mr. Trump spearheaded reducing the rate from 35% to 21%.Ms. Harris proposes increasing the top corporate rate from 21% to 28%, a 25% increase inincome tax ASTS would have to pay instead of investing in it's growth.Mr. Trump wants to maintain the current long-term capital gains tax on sales of ASTS stockat 15% and 20% for higher earners.Ms. Harris proposes taxing capital gains taxes as ordinary earnings. So an investor in the 28% marginal income tax bracket would see in increase in capital gains taxes on ASTS stock sales from 15% to 28%, almost doubling the tax owed. Ms. Harris also proposes, with Mr. Biden,to impose the tax on "unrealized" gains, on ASTS stock that an investor owns but has not yetsold. The unrealized gain tax would be imposed on higher earners.Mr. Trump lowered personal income tax brackets across the board in 2017. Those reductions will "sunset" (end) in 2025 if they are not renewed. Mr. Trump wants to renew them. Ms. Harris avoids the subject, but Mr. Biden has expressed disdain for the 2017 reductions. The increased standard deduction would also sunset. If the brackets sunset and increase to the pre-2017 levels, so too would the cap-gains tax with Harris's proposal.

$ASTS: It's entertaining to see SpaceX and T-Mobile scrambling to have power limits raised for their D2C satellites.  It's important to understand that the FCC's Supplemental Coverage from Space (SCS) was established as SECONDARY to terrestrial mobile service.  Satellite companies are required to ensure SCS deployment doesn't interfere with existing terrestrial mobile networks.

Recently, SpaceX and T-Mobile have pursued a FCC waiver on the aggregate out-of-band omission (OOBE) power-flux density (PFD) limits and requested an almost nine-fold increase in the already allowed limit by regulations. Why? Because SpaceX is coming to the realization that its Direct-to-Cellular satellites that were quickly slapped together utilizing technology from SpaceX's acquisition of Swarm, a low bandwidth IoT LEO satellite startup that became infamous for becoming the first US company to have deployed satellites without regulatory approval in 2018, CAN'T WORK UNLESS THE FCC POWER LIMITS ARE INCREASED.  Swarm's technology was never designed to work with unmodified mobile phones utilizing terrestrial cellular spectrum.

Now SpaceX and T-Mobile find themselves in the unenviable spot of convincing the FCC that the power limits, that THEY HELPED CREATE to protect terrestrial networks, be raised so that their D2C satellites can work. These power limits were developed as part of the SCS regulatory framework that both SpaceX and T-Mobile helped shape along with other industry players a year ago!  Yes you read that right, SpaceX and T-Mobile agreed to these limits, but are now coming back hat in hand asking the limits to be increased.  You can't make this up.

While some SpaceX supporters may brush this off as a move by industry incumbents to stifle innovation and block out a potential new competitor, it's important to note that T-Mobile raised interference concerns with the FCC about AST SpaceMobile's application for its new D2C service in November 2020.

T-Mobile stated in 2020: "AST‚Äôs Petition for Declaratory Ruling is ultimately unnecessary to achieve many of the stated public interest benefits, as T-Mobile is already addressing the issues AST seeks to address with the instant request, specifically the deployment of affordable wireless broadband service to unserved or underserved rural areas and enhancing competition in these areas.  Rather than bridging the Digital Divide, granting the Petition for Declaratory Ruling could exacerbate deployment to these areas by impeding a well-established, well-funded and technologically sound deployment due to harmful interference. "

AST has addressed these concerns through multiple interference studies and test results, and from the beginning architected its solution to work with existing terrestrial networks and subsequently meets the FCC SCS interference requirements. 

Imagine that! AST SpaceMobile and other satellite operators are all working within the regulatory framework EVERYONE AGREED TO, but SpaceX and T-Mobile are now asking for the rules to be changed because their technology doesn't work.

The best bit of advice I heard regarding timing an exit is 'always leave something for the next man'. Applies to any transaction. Particularly when a stock has gone parabolic like ASTS. If there is no obvious upside left for the next buyer then you are at the market top. If everyone stampedes of the exit at the same time then a fall can be self fulfilling and fuel an overshoot on the way down. There's no shame of selling and buying back in at a higher (or lower) price when new events have changed.
